   <xocs:rawtext>CHEMICAL PHYSICS LETTERS  25 December 1987  Volume 142, number 6  AN SCF Xx SW CALCULATION OF Pt X-RAY ABSORPTION SPECFRA  IN CHLORIDE COMPLEXES: PRE-EDGE STRUCTURE, XANES AND EXAFS    A.V. KONDRATENKO, V.1. NEMANOYA, N.Y. BAUSK, L.N. MAZALOY  Institute of !norganic Chemistry, Siberian Branch of the USSR Academy of Sciences, 630090 Novosibirsk, USSR      S.E RUZANKIN and G.M. ZHYDOMIROY  Institute of Catalysis, Siberian Branch of the USSR Academy of Sciences, 630090 Novosibirsk, USSR      Received 26 August 1987; in final form 14 October 1987         The results of an SCF Xa SW calculation of Pt L, and L23 X-ray absorption spectra in the complexes PtC1~ and PtCt at  photoelectron energies from  20 to + 210 eV have revealed the main details of the pre-edge structure and the origins of XANES  and EXAFS.  1. Introduction     In the past decade X-ray absorption spectroscopy  has developed into an effective tool for local struc-  turc analysis [1]. Information concerning the inter-  atomic distances is contained in the extended X-ray  absorption fine structure (EXAFS) [2] which cor-  responds to photoelectron energies e from about 50  to 1000 eV. In the single-scattering approximation  there exists n simple universal sine formula [2] which  relates the EXAFS parameters to the interatomic  distances. For this reason there is generally no need  to perform a precision quantum-chemical calcula-  tion to extract information on interatomic distances  from an experimental EXAFS; it suffices to fit to the  experimental EXAFS the results of a theoretical cal-  culation using this formula with varying interatomic  distances. However there may be cases, especially in  inorganic compounds, where the simple EXAFS for-  mula is no longer valid as a result, for example, of  large atomic charges in the coordination spheres  which obviates the use for these spheres of the scat-  tering amplitudes and phases calculated for neutral  atoms. There may also occur strong many-electron  effects which will complicate extraction of the atom  type, coordination numbers and other information  from the experimental EXAFS data [1]. It is also  desirable to know how an EXAFS experiment should  be carried out and its results processed in order to be  able to extract from the EXAFS data not only the  interatomic distances but also the bond angles, the  atom types and the coordination numbers and this  not only for the first shell but also for more distant  coordination spheres. It would also be of interest to  find a method which could help us to establish the  region where XANES goes over into EXAFS and also  where the simple sine formula is applicable to  EXAFS. There are a number of such questions which  are only amenable to precision quantum-chemical  calculations taking into account the details of both  the atomic and electronic structure.   We can take a wider look at this problem and con-  sider along with EXAFS also XANES and the pre-  edge structure. Due to the more involved nature of  the latter two structures, there seems to be no simple  practical working formula relating the fine structure  to the ammic structure. Consequently at the moment  we cannot do without wide application of quantum-  chemical calculations which are able to provide a  deeper insight into the mechanisms of XANES and  EXAFS formation and to establish, by comparing  one-electron data with experiment, how the spectra  are affected by many-electron processes.  509  Volume 142, number 6  CHEMICAL PHYSICS LETTERS  25 December 1987  2. Results of the calculations and experiments     A precise first-principles calculation of photoelec-  tron wavefunctions is a considerable quantum-  chemical problem. At the present time it can be  solved on a consistent basis only within the one-elec-  tron self-consistent-field Xa scattered wave (SCF Xa  SW) approach [3 5] in which both the pre-edge dis-  crete and the continuous (XANES and EXAFS) re-  gions are treated from a common viewpoint. In this  communication we present the results of an SCF Xa  SW calculation of the Pt X-ray absorption spectra of  some chloride complexes in the photoelectron en-  ergy region e from  20 to + 210 eV. The calculation  was performed using the XaCONTINUOUS system  of programs [6]. The study enabled us to elucidate  the details of the origin of XANES and EXAFS, to  reveal the dynamics of the change from the narrow  shape rescnances of XANES to the broad EXAFS  oscillations and to outline, by comparing theory with  experiment, the role of many-electron effects in the  continuous absorption region of the spectra.   Details of the calculational procedure are as fol-  lows: The exchange parameters a used were  Hartree Fock [7] ones both in the bound and con-  tinuous states; the basis set included harmonics with  angular momenta Ic 5 and 11c 12 for the bound (and,  hence, for the electron potential) and continuous  state, respectively. All spectra were calculated in a  self-consistent potential for the ground state of com-  plexes with Norman radii [8,9] for the atomic and  outer spheres. The theoretical SCF Xa SW L1 and   0 40 8 D tb teo tio c,ev   12   PtL1 [PtcI4j  Fig. 1. The theoretical Pt L, absorption spectrum of the PtCU  complex. The dashed lines show the partial components of the  spectra without the natural width y of the inner originating level,  and the solid line represents the overall spectrum with y = 6 eV.  c,ev  Fig. 2. Theoretical Pt L23 (solid line, y = 4eV) and experimental  (dashed line, K2PtCI4 coordination compound) Pt L3 absorption  spectra of the PtC1L complex.      L2,3 (not taking into account the L2 L3 splitting) are  presented in figs. l 4, where they are compared with  our experimental Pt L3 data obtained using syn-  chrotron radiation at the Institute of Nuclear Phys-  ics of the Siberian Branch of the USSR Academy of  Sciences in Novosibirsk.   It can be seen from figs. 1 4 that whilst for the Pt  L2,3 spectra of the complexes, the