at  the maxima in the one-particle SCF Xa SW EXAFS  data are shifted to lower photoelectron energies as  compared with their experimental counterparts and  the theoretical EXAFS amplitude is substantially  larger than the experimental value, in good agree-  ment with the predictions of many-electron EXAFS  theory [11].  3. Discussion     As can be seen from figs. 2 and 4, the overall agree-  ment of the one-particle SCF Xa SW theory with ex-  periment for Pt L3 spectra is very satisfactory which  permits us to assign all of the maxima and to clarify  the main details of pre-edge structure and the mech-  anisms involved in the formation of XANES and  EXAFS. For example, the theory shows that the par-  tial spectral components resulting from transitions  to terminating states of various symmetries differ in  their behaviour as a function of the photoelectron  energy. In the near-edge region all partial compo-  nents may exhibit intense shape resonances whereas  in the high energy region the EXAFS oscillations are  observed only for those partial components which  have terminating continuous states with a spatial  diagram most closely resembling the complex ge-  ometry. The differences between SCF Xa SW theory  and experiment are due to many-electron effects.        References    [1] A. Bianconi, L. Incoccia and S. Stipcich, eds., Springer se-  ries in chemical physics, Vol. 27. Proceedings of the Inter-  national Conference on EXAFS and Near Edge Structure,  Frascati (1982) (Springer, Berlin, 1983).  [21 F.W. Lytle, DE. Sayers and E.A. Stern, Phys. Rev. 811  (1975) 4825.  [3] K.H. Johnson, Advan. Quantum Chem. 7 (1973) 143.  [4] D. Dill and J.L. Dehmer, J. Chem. Phys. 61(1974)692.  [5] F.W. Kutzler, C.R. Matou, D.K. Misemer, S. Doniach and  K.O. Hodgson, J. Chem. Phys. 73(1980)3274.  [6] S.F. Ruzankin, V.1. Nemanova and A.V. Kondratenko, Zh.  Strukt. Khim. 27 (1986) 162.  [7] K. Schwarz, Phys. Rev. B5 (1972) 2466.  [81 J.G. Norman Jr., J. Chem. Phys. 61(1974) 4630.  [